= Employed ArchiMate elements

For the representation of the workflow, we adopt a subset of the ArchiMate language footnote:[http://www.hosiaisluoma.fi/ArchiMate-Cookbook.pdf], which is an open and independent enterprise architecture modelling language to support the description, analysis and visualisation of architecture within and across business domains in a clear and unambiguous way.

For this work a basic ArchiMate design pattern was used. Specifically, this design pattern includes:

== The Business Layer
The Business Layer contains:

** _Stakeholders (Business Actors)_ : A business Actor represents a business entity that is capable of performing behaviour.


image::data:image/png;base64,[]



** _Business Processes_:A Business process represents a sequence of business behaviours that achieves a specific result such as a defined set of products or business services.


image::data:image/png;base64,[]



* _Business objects_: A Business Object represents a concept used within a particular business domain.


image::data:image/png;base64,[]



== The Application Layer
The Application Layer contains:

** _Application Components_: An Application Component represents an encapsulation of application functionality aligned to implementation structure, which is modular and replaceable.


image::data:image/png;base64,[]



** _Data Objects:_ A Data Object represents data structured for automated
Processing. Example: A Data specification artefact. Note, that although ePO Artefacts should normally be represented as Artefacts, they were omitted from the diagrams for simplicitys sake. They are thus represented as Business Objects and Data Objects.


image::data:image/png;base64,[]



== The Technology Layer
The Technology Layer contains:

** _Nodes:_ A Node represents a computational or physical resource that hosts, manipulates, or interacts with other computational or physical
Resources. Example: A GitHub repository.


image::data:image/png;base64,[]



** _System Software:_ Represents software that provides or contributes to an environment for storing, executing, and using software or data deployed within it. Example: GitHub Actions.



image::data:image/png;base64,[]



* _Device:_ Represents a physical IT resource upon which system software and artefacts may be stored or deployed for execution. Example: PC.


image::data:image/png;base64,[]



* _Technology service_: Represents an explicitly defined exposed technological behaviour. Example: model2owl.


image::data:image/png;base64,[]



* _Artefact_: Represents a piece of data that is used or produced in a software development process, or by deployment and operation of an IT system.  Example: model2Owl Scripts. Note, that although ePO Artefacts should normally be represented as Artefacts, they were omitted from the diagrams for simplicitys sake. They are thus represented as Business Objects and Data Objects.


image::data:image/png;base64,[]


== Structural Relationships

** _Composition_: Represents that an element consists of one or more other concepts.


image::data:image/png;base64,[]


** _Aggregation_: Represents that an element combines one or more other concepts.


image::data:image/png;base64,[]


** _Assignment_: Represents the allocation of responsibility, performance of behaviour, storage, or execution.


image::data:image/png;base64,[]


** _Realisation_: Represents that an entity plays a critical role in the creation, achievement, sustenance, or operation of a more abstract entity.


image::data:image/png;base64,[]




== Dependency Relationships

** _Serving_: Represents that an element provides its functionality to another element.


image::data:image/png;base64,[]


** _Access_:__ __Represents the ability of behaviour to observe or act upon passive structure elements.
For the purposes of the workflow, we use access relationship to denote that a Business Process has a specific Business object as
input AND that a Business Process has a specific Business object as output.

image::data:image/png;base64,[]



** _Association_:__ __Represents an unspecified relationship, or one that is not represented by another ArchiMate relationship.


image::data:image/png;base64,[]



== Dynamic Relationships

** _Triggering:_ Represents a temporal or causal relationship between elements.


image::data:image/png;base64,[]


**  Flow: Represents transfer from one element to another.



image::data:image/png;base64,[]


== Other Relationships

** _Specialisation:_ Represents that an element is a particular kind of another element.


image::data:image/png;base64,[]

** _Junction:_ Used to connect relationships of the same type.



image::data:image/png;base64,[]

For more information on the used elements please consult https://pubs.opengroup.org/architecture/archimate3-doc/ch-Generic-Metamodel.html#sec-Summary-of-Structure-and-Behavior-Elements[this summary]
